  {
    "language": "English",
    "entry_date": "2026-03-09T08:01:14Z",
    "report_number": "UoM--18941",
    "identifier": "SC0018941",
    "country_publication": "United States",
    "doi": "10.2172/2513436",
    "description": "This project focuses on the development of \u003cem\u003estimuli-responsive\u003c/em\u003e hybrid \u003cem\u003emultifunctional\u003c/em\u003e materials. We place emphasis on the design, synthesis, structural characterization, evaluation of functional properties (electronic, thermal and optical) of several (1-x)Cu\u003csub\u003e2\u003c/sub\u003eSe/(x)WBGS \u003cem\u003ehierarchical bulk composites between\u003c/em\u003e Cu\u003csub\u003e2\u003c/sub\u003eSe, a narrow band gap semiconductor (NBGS), with a range of wider band gap semiconductors (WBGS) such as CuMSe\u003csub\u003e2\u003c/sub\u003e (M \u003d Al, Ga, In, Fe, Cr) and Cu\u003csub\u003e4\u003c/sub\u003eTiSe\u003csub\u003e4\u003c/sub\u003e. Cu2Se is a well-studied NBGS with excellent thermoelectric properties (high electrical conductivity, large thermopower, etc.) while CuMSe\u003csub\u003e2\u003c/sub\u003e and Cu\u003csub\u003e4\u003c/sub\u003eTiSe\u003csub\u003e4\u003c/sub\u003e are high performance solar absorber materials (large band gap, large absorption coefficient, etc.). Our primary objectives are (i) to demonstrate the ability to integrate dissimilar functional properties such as large optical absorption coefficient and high electronic conductivity, within (1-x)Cu\u003csub\u003e2\u003c/sub\u003eSe/(x)WBGS composite; and (ii) to establish the correlation between the hierarchical structural entanglement of Cu\u003csub\u003e2\u003c/sub\u003eSe with WBGS (CuMSe\u003csub\u003e2\u003c/sub\u003e or Cu\u003csub\u003e4\u003c/sub\u003eTiSe\u003csub\u003e4\u003c/sub\u003e) phase, the interactions between native electronic defects within the coexisting phases in the resulting (1-x)Cu\u003csub\u003e2\u003c/sub\u003eSe/(x)WBGS \u003cem\u003ebulk composites\u003c/em\u003e, and the impacts on their electronic conductivity, thermal transport and optical properties.",
    "title": "Hierarchical Hybrid Multifunctional Materials through Interface Engineering",
    "contract_number": "SC0018941; ",
    "publication_date": "2025-02-10T00:00:00Z",
    "osti_id": "2513436",
    "product_type": "Technical Report",
    "authors": [
      "Poudeu, Pierre Ferdinand [Univ. of Michigan, Ann Arbor, MI (United States)]",
      "Uher, Ctirad [Univ. of Michigan, Ann Arbor, MI (United States)]"
    ],
    "subjects": [
      "36 MATERIALS SCIENCE",
      "double carrier transport processes at the interfaces",
      "Hiearchical composites",
      "native defects interactions and hybridizations",
      "negative photoconductivity",
      "photon coherence in bulk nanocomposites",
      "temperature induced p-type to n-type electronic transitions"
    ],
